{"id":"2201.01117","submitter":"Zeev Rudnick","authors":"Ze\\'ev Rudnick and Igor Wigman","title":"On the Robin spectrum for the equilateral triangle","comments":"revised version. Added one figure. Accepted for publication in\n  Journal of Physics A, special issue \"Claritons and Asymptotics of Ideas: The\n  Physics of Michael Berry\"","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1751-8121/ac6f9b","report-no":null,"categories":"math.SP math-ph math.MP math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The equilateral triangle is one of the few planar domains where the Dirichlet\nand Neumann eigenvalue problems were explicitly determined, by Lam\\'e in 1833,\ndespite not admitting separation of variables. In this paper, we study the\nRobin spectrum of the equilateral triangle, which was determined by McCartin in\n2004 in terms of a system of transcendental coupled secular equations.\n  We give uniform upper bounds for the Robin-Neumann gaps, showing that they\nare bounded by their limiting mean value, which is hence an almost sure bound.\nThe spectrum admits a systematic double multiplicity, and after removing it we\nstudy the gaps in the resulting desymmetrized spectrum. We show a spectral gap\nproperty, that there are arbitrarily large gaps, and also arbitrarily small\nones, moreover that the nearest neighbour spacing distribution of the\ndesymmetrized spectrum is a delta function at the origin. We show that for\nsufficiently small Robin parameter, the desymmetrized spectrum is simple.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Jan 2022 12:56:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 28 Apr 2022 20:36:06 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-06-15"}
